{"expireTime":9007200932796145000,"key":"transformer-remark-markdown-ast-c889a4d5124b770f6b91651fa0732316-gatsby-remark-imagesgatsby-remark-responsive-iframegatsby-remark-prismjsgatsby-remark-copy-linked-filesgatsby-remark-smartypants-/blog","val":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"image","title":null,"url":"https://farm1.staticflickr.com/516/19886792840_5f1cf77465_z.jpg","alt":null,"position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1,"offset":0},"end":{"line":1,"column":69,"offset":68},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1,"offset":0},"end":{"line":1,"column":69,"offset":68},"indent":[]}},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"This is extremely lazy, but (from ","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1,"offset":70},"end":{"line":3,"column":35,"offset":104},"indent":[]}},{"type":"link","title":null,"url":"http://www.moma.org/visit/calendar/exhibitions/1527","children":[{"type":"text","value":"MoMA.org","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":36,"offset":105},"end":{"line":3,"column":44,"offset":113},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":35,"offset":104},"end":{"line":3,"column":98,"offset":167},"indent":[]}},{"type":"text","value":"):","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":98,"offset":167},"end":{"line":3,"column":100,"offset":169},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1,"offset":70},"end":{"line":3,"column":100,"offset":169},"indent":[]}},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"emphasis","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Analogue","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":2,"offset":172},"end":{"line":5,"column":10,"offset":180},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1,"offset":171},"end":{"line":5,"column":11,"offset":181},"indent":[]}},{"type":"text","value":", by Zoe Leonard (American, b. 1961), is a landmark project comprising 412 photographs conceived over the course of a decade. Displayed in serial grids and organized into 25 chapters, ","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":11,"offset":181},"end":{"line":5,"column":195,"offset":365},"indent":[]}},{"type":"emphasis","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Analogue","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":196,"offset":366},"end":{"line":5,"column":204,"offset":374},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":195,"offset":365},"end":{"line":5,"column":205,"offset":375},"indent":[]}},{"type":"text","value":" documents the eclipsed texture of 20th-century urban life as seen in vanishing mom-and-pop stores and the simultaneous emergence of the global rag trade. Leonard took her own New York neighborhood, Manhattan’s Lower East Side, as a point of departure in the late 1990s. She then followed the circulation of recycled merchandise—used clothing, discarded advertisements, and the old technology of Kodak camera shops—to far-flung markets in Africa, Eastern Europe, Cuba, Mexico, and the Middle East.","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":205,"offset":375},"end":{"line":5,"column":702,"offset":872},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1,"offset":171},"end":{"line":5,"column":702,"offset":872},"indent":[]}},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"The disappearing storefronts and neglected products are echoed in the obsolete technology the artist used to reproduce them: a vintage 1940s Rolleiflex camera, a tool “left over from the mechanical age,” as Leonard put it, along with gelatin silver and chromogenic printing processes. Tapping the traditions of documentary and conceptual photography, ","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1,"offset":874},"end":{"line":7,"column":352,"offset":1225},"indent":[]}},{"type":"emphasis","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Analogue","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":353,"offset":1226},"end":{"line":7,"column":361,"offset":1234},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":352,"offset":1225},"end":{"line":7,"column":362,"offset":1235},"indent":[]}},{"type":"text","value":" is positioned in the genealogy of grand visual archives that extends from Eugène Atget’s compendium of Paris to Martha Rosler’s photo-text work on New York’s Bowery. Leonard’s project is an urgent document and a poetic allegory of globalization that reveals the circulation of goods and the homogenization of diverse geographical locations in the 21st century.","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":362,"offset":1235},"end":{"line":7,"column":723,"offset":1596},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1,"offset":874},"end":{"line":7,"column":723,"offset":1596},"indent":[]}},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"In my own crappy words: There’s some beauty about capturing things as they fade into obsolescence. It especially resonates for me because I worked a bit on the Kodak bankruptcy/restructuring case–so here all of my worlds are colliding as these photos are plastered to the walls of my new workplace.","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1,"offset":1598},"end":{"line":9,"column":299,"offset":1896},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1,"offset":1598},"end":{"line":9,"column":299,"offset":1896},"indent":[]}},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Zoe Leonard: ","position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1,"offset":1898},"end":{"line":11,"column":14,"offset":1911},"indent":[]}},{"type":"emphasis","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Analogue","position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":15,"offset":1912},"end":{"line":11,"column":23,"offset":1920},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":14,"offset":1911},"end":{"line":11,"column":24,"offset":1921},"indent":[]}},{"type":"text","value":" runs through August 30, 2015.","position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":24,"offset":1921},"end":{"line":11,"column":54,"offset":1951},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1,"offset":1898},"end":{"line":11,"column":54,"offset":1951},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1,"offset":0},"end":{"line":1